38:53.600 --> 38:54.866 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
a rookie error.

38:54.866 --> 38:57.033 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
Do you buy that as an excuse?

38:57.033 --> 38:58.433 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
REP.

38:58.433 --> 38:59.866 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
ADAM SCHIFF: Well, he doesn't
strike me as a rookie.

38:59.866 --> 39:01.800 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
I think he's quite
sophisticated.

39:01.800 --> 39:03.933 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
I don't want to
characterize his testimony.

39:03.933 --> 39:06.733 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
We actually don't really go
into the details of testimony.

39:06.733 --> 39:10.033 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
I was surprised that
my colleague was
willing to do that.

39:10.033 --> 39:15.033 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
I will say this, that the holder
of that clearance, I do believe,
needs to investigate this to

39:17.066 --> 39:21.600 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
find out whether Mr. Kushner's
explanations are satisfactory,
what the circumstances are,

39:22.966 --> 39:25.433 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
what was disclosed,
what wasn't disclosed.

39:25.433 --> 39:28.266 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
We have not yet
obtained the SF-86s.

39:28.266 --> 39:33.266 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So we're really not in a
position to evaluate what
and when he disclosed
different things.

39:35.233 --> 39:38.566 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
But I do believe that other
individuals, not the son-in-law
of the president, if they were

39:40.566 --> 39:44.366 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
to fail to disclose a meeting
that they attended that was with
people acting on behalf of the

39:46.400 --> 39:50.533 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Russian government, promising
dirt on a political opponent, or
a meeting that wasn't disclosed

39:50.533 --> 39:55.533 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
that involved setting up a
secret back channel at a Russian
diplomatic facility, it is very

39:57.500 --> 39:59.600 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
unlikely that an ordinary
individual would be allowed
to keep their clearance.

39:59.600 --> 40:03.533 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: Let's touch
on a few other issues that are
swirling in Washington right

40:03.533 --> 40:05.633 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
now.

40:05.633 --> 40:08.166 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Obviously, as you have been
hearing in our broadcast, the
president has been very tough

40:08.166 --> 40:10.266 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
on Attorney General Sessions.

40:10.266 --> 40:13.666 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Many people believe that the
president would like him to
either leave or would like to

40:13.666 --> 40:15.666 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
fire him.

40:15.666 --> 40:18.833 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
If that were to happen,
what would that do to these
ongoing investigations?

40:18.833 --> 40:20.100 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
REP.

40:20.100 --> 40:22.200 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
ADAM SCHIFF: Well, I
think you're right.

40:22.200 --> 40:25.200 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
In this case, the president
is being very transparent, at
least as far as his intentions

40:25.200 --> 40:27.300 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
are concerned.

40:27.300 --> 40:31.233 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
He wants to force Jeff Sessions
to resign, and, therefore, he
would less have his fingerprints

40:31.233 --> 40:34.133 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
on hit than if he
fired Jeff Sessions.

40:34.133 --> 40:36.900 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
And I think the motivation
is quite simple.

40:36.900 --> 40:41.633 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
He wants to appoint a
more malleable attorney
general when it comes to
the Russia investigation

40:41.633 --> 40:45.733 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
who is not recused, who can
tell Bob Mueller, you will look
at this, but you won't look

40:45.733 --> 40:50.466 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
at these other areas that are
evidently so concerning to the
president, including whether

40:50.466 --> 40:54.500 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
there was any money-laundering
going on with the
Trump Organization.

40:54.500 --> 40:56.633 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
What should we do about it?

40:56.633 --> 41:01.133 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
If there is any effort
to interfere with Bob
Mueller's investigation,
we may need to reenact

41:03.100 --> 41:06.500 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
the independent counsel law,
and make sure that Bob Mueller
has a completely free hand

41:08.500 --> 41:12.733 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
to look at anything relevant
to the Russia investigation
or that arises from it, which

41:14.500 --> 41:18.333 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
is his charter now, but
something clearly the president
is uncomfortable with.

41:20.400 --> 41:24.533 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
The president needs
to understand this is
not his prerogative
to determine what the

41:26.266 --> 41:28.200 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
investigators are
investigating when it
involves his own organization.

41:28.200 --> 41:30.833 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: I'm curious
what you think, though.

41:30.833 --> 41:35.833 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
The president has said --
what's really relevant here is
probably what the GOP would do.

41:37.800 --> 41:42.000 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
If Sessions were fired, we heard
today many, many senators and
congressmen supporting Jeff

41:44.466 --> 41:47.766 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Sessions, but we also
heard Speaker Ryan saying
that, in essence, it
is the president's job

41:47.766 --> 41:50.100 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
to determine who
is in his Cabinet.

41:50.100 --> 41:55.100 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Do you think if this -- if
Sessions were to be let go, that
the GOP would -- there would

41:56.000 --> 41:57.033 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
be a revolt in his own party?

41:57.033 --> 41:59.166 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
REP.

41:59.166 --> 42:01.900 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
ADAM SCHIFF: I would certainly
hope that that would be the
case, if he either pushes Jeff

42:01.900 --> 42:06.900 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Sessions out or he were to
fire Bob Mueller, that both
Democrats and Republicans would

42:08.833 --> 42:13.166 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
rise to their institutional
responsibility of insisting that
an independent investigation

42:13.166 --> 42:14.433 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
go forth.

42:14.433 --> 42:16.466 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
I think it would be a
constitutional crisis.

42:16.466 --> 42:19.866 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And I have to say, I'm deeply
disappointed once again to
hear the speaker so downplay

42:19.866 --> 42:24.833 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
the significance of this,
because that only encourages the
president to engage in conduct

42:24.833 --> 42:29.833 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
which is, I think, very
seriously at odds with our
system of checks and balances.

42:31.833 --> 42:34.633 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
When we meet with emerging
democracies, we always
emphasize a couple things.

42:34.633 --> 42:39.400 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
We emphasize, when you
win an election, you don't
jail the losing party.

42:39.400 --> 42:43.966 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And, here, one of the gripes
apparently the president has
is that Jeff Sessions is not

42:43.966 --> 42:48.200 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
acting to try to
investigate and prosecute
his political opponent.

42:48.200 --> 42:53.200 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
That is something you see
in a banana republic, not in
the United States of America.

42:54.600 --> 42:56.200 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
So, members of both
parties need to speak out.

42:56.200 --> 42:59.566 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
We shouldn't wait until
there is a crisis to do so.

42:59.566 --> 43:02.133 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
And I hope the speaker
will think better of
what he just said.

43:02.133 --> 43:06.733 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: Lastly,
quickly, Congressman,
the president clearly
still chafes at this

43:06.733 --> 43:09.133 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
Russia investigation.

43:09.133 --> 43:13.533 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And his new communications
director today seemed
to indicate that
the president still

43:15.433 --> 43:19.400 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
doesn't believe that Russia
was actually involved in trying
to meddle in our election.

43:21.766 --> 43:24.800 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Given that huge chasm
between what our intelligence
agencies believe and what
the president believes,

43:26.233 --> 43:29.033 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
how can this really go forward?

43:29.033 --> 43:31.100 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
REP.

43:31.100 --> 43:32.600 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
ADAM SCHIFF: Well, look, there
is only really one person in
America that doesn't believe

43:32.600 --> 43:34.133 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
the Russians were involved
in hacking our election.

43:34.133 --> 43:36.200 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
And that's, unfortunately,
the president.

43:36.200 --> 43:40.300 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Even Vladimir Putin, of course,
knows exactly what he's done,
so Russia is under no illusion

43:40.300 --> 43:41.833 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
about this.

43:41.833 --> 43:44.233 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
What does this
mean going forward?

43:44.233 --> 43:48.366 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
It means, of greater
significance to the
country, that we are not
taking the steps to prepare

43:49.700 --> 43:52.166 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
ourselves when the
Russians intervene again.

43:52.166 --> 43:56.133 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And that is very serious,
because there is no
software patch here.

43:56.133 --> 44:00.333 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
We're not going to be able
to make the DNC or the RNC
immune from Russian hacking.

44:00.333 --> 44:03.600 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
They're too good, and it's
too difficult to defend.

44:03.600 --> 44:08.600 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The only real defense the
country has is to bring
the country together
to forge a consensus

44:10.600 --> 44:13.133 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
that, no matter who it helps
or who it hurts, we will
reject foreign interference.

44:13.133 --> 44:17.966 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And our president is simply
not doing that, and this is
exposing us to further harm.

44:17.966 --> 44:20.933 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: All right,
Congressman Adam Schiff of
California, thanks very much.

44:20.933 --> 44:21.933 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
REP.

44:21.933 --> 44:25.400 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
ADAM SCHIFF: Thank you.

44:25.400 --> 44:30.400 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: For American
children, summer is supposed
to be a time of fun and games,

44:37.300 --> 44:40.600 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
but, for many, it is
also a time of true need.

44:40.600 --> 44:45.600 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
During the school year,
roughly 22 million children
in this country get
free and reduced-price

44:46.333 --> 44:47.766 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
lunch.

44:47.766 --> 44:50.300 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
In the summer, those
numbers drop dramatically.

44:50.300 --> 44:53.933 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Just under four million have
access to subsidized meals.

44:53.933 --> 44:58.933 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
There are 50,000 locations
providing summer meals, but
reaching those who need the food

44:59.666 --> 45:01.800 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
can be a challenge.

45:01.800 --> 45:06.500 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Special PBS correspondent Lisa
Stark of our partner Education
Week traveled to Nebraska

45:07.933 --> 45:11.233 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
to see how one food bank
is trying to fill the gap.

45:11.233 --> 45:16.233 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
LISA STARK: It's a scorching
summer day in Plattsmouth,
Nebraska, about 40 minutes south

45:17.866 --> 45:22.400 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
of Omaha, as the food
truck lumbers into view.

45:22.400 --> 45:26.766 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Despite the heat, families are
lining up for lunch at what's
called Kids Cruisin' Kitchen.

45:26.766 --> 45:29.300 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
BECKY HAM, Parent:
They get milk.

45:29.300 --> 45:31.433 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
They get fruit and vegetables.

45:31.433 --> 45:33.433 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
It's really a nice program.

45:33.433 --> 45:37.133 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
LISA STARK: Becky Ham and
her children rely on the food
truck a few times a week.

45:37.133 --> 45:41.166 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
BECKY HAM: We started doing this
about three summers ago when
my husband lost his job right

45:41.166 --> 45:43.400 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
before the end of
the school year.

45:43.400 --> 45:47.966 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And we were really panicked
about how we were going
to make everything work.

45:47.966 --> 45:52.466 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
LISA STARK: Ham's husband
has a new job, but the
budget remains tight.

45:52.466 --> 45:57.466 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
The family still qualifies for
free school lunches, and is
thankful for the summer help.

45:57.466 --> 45:59.633 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
BECKY HAM: It's really
helping kids out.

45:59.633 --> 46:02.266 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
It's really helping families
out when they need it.

46:02.266 --> 46:06.766 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
LISA STARK: Kids Cruisin'
Kitchen was launched six years
ago by Omaha's Food Bank for the

46:06.766 --> 46:09.200 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
Heartland and Salvation Army.

46:09.200 --> 46:14.200 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
With four food trucks and
10 fixed locations, it
serves 1,300 children a day.

46:15.366 --> 46:18.333 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
Do you get enough to
eat at the food truck?

46:18.333 --> 46:21.966 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
CHILD: MD-U They
give us a lot of meals.

46:21.966 --> 46:23.800 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
LISA STARK: A lot of
meals and a lot of food?

46:23.800 --> 46:24.900 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
CHILD: MD-U Yes.

46:24.900 --> 46:26.166 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
LISA STARK: Yes?

46:26.166 --> 46:28.033 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
Susan Ogborn is the
food bank president.

46:28.033 --> 46:29.300 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
Who are you trying to help?

46:29.300 --> 46:31.300 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
Who's your target here
for the summer meals?

46:31.300 --> 46:33.033 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
SUSAN OGBORN, President,
Food Bank for the Heartland:
Primarily, the children of the

46:33.033 --> 46:34.566 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
working poor.

46:34.566 --> 46:37.633 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
They are the folks who won't
tell you that they need help.

46:37.633 --> 46:41.733 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
They are the folks whose
children qualify for free
or reduced price-lunches.

46:41.733 --> 46:46.733 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
LISA STARK: Preparing
these meals begins early
in the morning in an
industrial kitchen run

46:47.666 --> 46:49.700 align:left position:25%,start line:86.67% size:75%
by an Omaha area
school district.

46:49.700 --> 46:53.566 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
They make meals for Kids
Cruisin' Kitchen and other
summer meal programs.

46:53.566 --> 46:56.933 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JACKIE CAMBRIDGE, Meal Service
Manager: We do about 3,000
meals a day during the summer.

46:56.933 --> 47:01.933 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
LISA STARK: In less than three
hours on this morning, corn
dogs are cooked, bananas packed,

47:03.833 --> 47:07.033 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
chocolate milk readied, sack
lunches bagged, chicken patties,
fruit and veggies prepped

47:07.033 --> 47:08.300 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
for later in the week.

47:08.300 --> 47:10.166 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
JACKIE CAMBRIDGE: It's
the five food groups.

47:10.166 --> 47:13.400 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
It's grains, meat,
fruit, vegetables, milk.

47:13.400 --> 47:18.400 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
LISA STARK: Meals are paid
for by the U.S. Department of
Agriculture, $3.83 each, and

47:20.266 --> 47:25.100 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
must meet government nutrition
standards, which are a
bit looser in the summer.

47:26.533 --> 47:28.500 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Jackie Cambridge manages
this summer meal service.

47:28.500 --> 47:33.333 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JACKIE CAMBRIDGE: There's
always a whew when we
get it out the door.

47:35.333 --> 47:38.833 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And then we just hope that
it's getting to kids in need,
and that they're enjoying it,

47:38.833 --> 47:40.833 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
and we do it all
again the next day.

47:40.833 --> 47:45.766 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
LISA STARK: Shortly after 9:00
a.m., the Kids Cruisin' Kitchen
truck pulls up to load its

47:46.500 --> 47:48.533 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
food, hot meals to go.

47:48.533 --> 47:52.933 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
The truck makes four
stops each weekday during
most of the summer break.

47:52.933 --> 47:57.166 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
After that first stop
in Plattsmouth, it's
off to a public library,
followed by a public

47:57.166 --> 48:02.166 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
housing project, then onto an
affordable housing development,
areas where more than half of

48:04.133 --> 48:07.800 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
children quality for free
and reduced-price lunch,
although anyone is welcome.

48:08.666 --> 48:13.166 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
CHILD: You got corn dogs today?

48:13.166 --> 48:15.233 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
Bananas.

48:15.233 --> 48:18.833 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
LISA STARK: Summer lunches
are an outgrowth of subsidized
school lunches, which expanded

48:18.833 --> 48:20.800 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
in the 1960s.

48:20.800 --> 48:24.366 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
NARRATOR: A good lunch provides
from a third to one-half of
the student's daily needs.

48:24.366 --> 48:27.566 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
LISA STARK: As part of President
Lyndon Johnson's war on poverty.

48:27.566 --> 48:32.566 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
LYNDON JOHNSON, Former President
of the United States: Children
just must not go hungry.

48:33.733 --> 48:35.933 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
LISA STARK: The programs
have grown enormously.

48:35.933 --> 48:40.933 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Today, 85 percent of all
breakfasts served at schools
and 73 percent of school lunches

48:42.900 --> 48:46.566 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
are subsidized by the USDA;
12 million students depend on
breakfast, 22 million on lunch.

48:49.066 --> 48:54.066 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Nationwide, nearly 20
percent of children under
age 18 live in poverty.

48:54.933 --> 48:56.933 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
That's 14.5 million children.

48:56.933 --> 49:00.866 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
LAURA HATCH, No Kid Hungry:
Sometimes, schools are providing
the only meals that kids get

49:00.866 --> 49:02.866 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
during the week.

49:02.866 --> 49:06.833 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
LISA STARK: Laura Hatch is
With No Kid Hungry, a national
advocacy group trying to reduce

49:07.566 --> 49:08.833 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
childhood hunger.

49:08.833 --> 49:10.900 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
She says school meals
make a big difference.

49:10.900 --> 49:14.966 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
LAURA HATCH: We know that
kids that eat breakfast
do better on math tests.

49:14.966 --> 49:19.900 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
We know that serving breakfast
as part of the school day can
actually keep kids in their

49:19.900 --> 49:21.966 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
seat and lessen absenteeism.

49:21.966 --> 49:25.000 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
LISA STARK: Serving
school meals is easier.

49:25.000 --> 49:26.733 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
Students are all in one place.

49:26.733 --> 49:28.233 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
Summer meals are tougher.

49:28.233 --> 49:30.733 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
The food has to get to
where the children are.

49:30.733 --> 49:35.733 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
To make it work, the food bank
hires 10 temporary staffers, and
relies on 200 volunteers from

49:36.833 --> 49:38.566 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
Mutual of Omaha.

49:38.566 --> 49:41.266 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
This is Gary Hering's
third year helping out.

49:41.266 --> 49:43.400 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
He understands hunger.

49:43.400 --> 49:46.233 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
GARY HERING, Volunteer: There
were times when, as a family,
I know we struggled, and we'd

49:46.233 --> 49:48.900 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
go visit relatives just to eat,
you know, have food every day.

49:48.900 --> 49:50.966 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
LISA STARK: Do you think that's
true for some of these kids?

49:50.966 --> 49:51.966 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
Or what do you think?

49:51.966 --> 49:54.066 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
GARY HERING: You bet.

49:54.066 --> 49:56.233 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
That's the best part about it
today, that these kids aren't
going to be hungry at lunch.

49:56.233 --> 50:00.333 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
LISA STARK: Despite all this
effort by the food bank and
others, Nebraska ranks near

50:00.333 --> 50:04.466 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
the bottom of all 50 states
when it comes to summer meals.

50:04.466 --> 50:09.466 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
For every 100 children
who depend on the school
lunch program, only
eight are getting help

50:10.700 --> 50:12.833 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
during the summer.

50:12.833 --> 50:16.866 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
That's according to the Food
Research and Action Network,
which found that, last year,

50:18.866 --> 50:22.500 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
nationwide, that gap between
filling the need during the
school year and the summer got

50:23.200 --> 50:24.700 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
wider.

50:24.700 --> 50:27.500 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
It's especially difficult to
reach children in rural areas.

50:27.500 --> 50:32.500 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
They are spread out, and USDA
rules require all summer meals
to be served and eaten in

50:33.233 --> 50:35.600 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
one place at one time.

50:35.600 --> 50:38.366 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
WOMAN: You guys going to
eat it over here today, OK?

50:38.366 --> 50:42.266 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
LISA STARK: Regulars, like
Michelle Brown and her sisters,
are well aware of the rules.

50:42.266 --> 50:45.800 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
CHILD: You just have to,
like, eat here, and you
have to come on time.

50:45.800 --> 50:50.800 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
LISA STARK: USDA has a pilot
program in seven states and two
tribal areas to help families

50:52.833 --> 50:56.733 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
in need during the summer
by temporarily increasing
food stamps benefits.

50:58.200 --> 51:01.300 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Advocates would like this
program offered more widely.

51:01.300 --> 51:06.300 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Agriculture Secretary Sonny
Perdue, who recently visited a
summer meal site in Washington,

51:07.466 --> 51:09.466 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
D.C., says he's
open to the idea.

51:09.466 --> 51:12.000 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
SONNY PERDUE, U.S. Agriculture
Secretary: I don't think
any of us want to fast over

51:12.000 --> 51:17.000 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
the summer, so just because
school stops doesn't mean that
the needs for good, nutritious,

51:18.433 --> 51:20.500 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
healthy food and a good
environment doesn't stop.

51:20.500 --> 51:25.166 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
LISA STARK: The food bank's
Susan Ogborn is eager to see
regulations relaxed to make it

51:26.033 --> 51:27.566 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
easier to expand summer meals.

51:27.566 --> 51:30.233 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
SUSAN OGBORN: The problem is,
children are hungry every day.

51:30.233 --> 51:35.233 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And so we hope that Secretary
Perdue and the rest of his team
at USDA get their rules and

51:37.300 --> 51:39.400 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
regulations figured
out pretty quickly.

51:39.400 --> 51:43.633 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
LISA STARK: For now, the food
bank will continue to roll along
with its current program, hoping

51:46.166 --> 51:49.333 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
one day to reach many more
children, but committed
to the mostly satisfied
customers it already

51:50.866 --> 51:52.100 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
has.

51:52.100 --> 51:53.666 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
What do you think
about the food truck?

51:53.666 --> 51:58.233 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
CHILD: I like it, but I would
love it if they added donuts.

51:59.133 --> 52:01.533 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
LISA STARK: Maybe next summer.

52:01.533 --> 52:06.533 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
For the "PBS NewsHour" and
Education Week, I'm Lisa
Stark in Omaha, Nebraska.

52:07.733 --> 52:09.733 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
JUDY WOODRUFF: We
love donuts, too.

52:09.733 --> 52:12.133 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
