52:12.133 --> 52:17.000 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
Seawalls help to protect
developed shorelines,
but they can also
destroy crucial habitat.

52:17.000 --> 52:20.200 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
One project in Washington
state aims to fix that.

52:20.200 --> 52:24.100 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
Ken Christensen of
KCTS' EarthFix explains.

52:24.100 --> 52:29.100 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
KEN CHRISTENSEN: The Seattle
waterfront is changing
right beneath your feet.

52:31.033 --> 52:33.266 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JEFF CORDELL, University of
Washington: When you walk along
Seattle's sidewalk, you will

52:33.266 --> 52:35.266 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
be walking on glass panels.

52:35.266 --> 52:39.833 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
KEN CHRISTENSEN: But look
deeper, and you will see that
the changes aren't for tourists.

52:40.733 --> 52:42.833 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
They're for natives.

52:42.833 --> 52:46.733 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
JEFF CORDELL: Their
function is to provide
light to help thousands
and thousands of little

52:46.733 --> 52:48.800 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
baby salmon.

52:48.800 --> 52:52.733 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
KEN CHRISTENSEN: It's
one feature of Seattle's
new seawall, a $400
million infrastructure

52:54.800 --> 52:57.800 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
project that's doubling as a
really big science experiment,
the biggest of Jeff Cordell's

52:58.933 --> 53:00.466 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
career.

53:00.466 --> 53:02.433 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
JEFF CORDELL: Nothing has
ever been tried on this scale.

53:02.433 --> 53:06.533 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
You're walking on foot after
foot after foot of new habitat.

53:06.533 --> 53:11.533 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
KEN CHRISTENSEN: Cordell wants
to see if coastal cities can
better coexist with fish.

53:13.533 --> 53:16.666 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
For 80 years, Seattle's seawall
was like most, a flat, concrete
slab that held back the sea,

53:18.200 --> 53:22.300 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
but destroyed shallow
water habitat that
many species thrive on.

53:22.300 --> 53:27.300 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Every spring, young salmon
would migrate from Seattle's
Duwamish River to the ocean, and

53:29.300 --> 53:32.833 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
they're hard-wired to stay
close to shore, which means
they run right into this.

53:34.766 --> 53:38.733 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
In the inky darkness
under the pier, life can
get confusing for a fish.

53:38.733 --> 53:42.466 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
JEFF CORDELL: There's
a good example of a
shadow line from a pier.

53:42.466 --> 53:46.066 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And they don't want to
cross the shadow line, so
they just mill about here.

53:46.066 --> 53:50.633 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
KEN CHRISTENSEN: The new
seawall is supposed to make life
easier, not only by providing

53:50.633 --> 53:55.400 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
a naturally lit corridor for
fish to pass through on their
way to the ocean, but also

53:55.400 --> 54:00.233 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
by featuring overhangs and
rocky surfaces along the way
for fish food to grow on.

54:00.233 --> 54:02.366 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
JEFF CORDELL: Look at
the brown scum here.

54:02.366 --> 54:06.566 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
We love to see that,
because that's where
the little crustaceans
grow that the juvenile

54:06.566 --> 54:08.033 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
salmon feed on.

54:08.033 --> 54:10.466 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
You can't count out brown scum.

54:10.466 --> 54:15.433 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
KEN CHRISTENSEN: Most seawalls
are still get built like
Seattle's was back in the 1930s.

54:15.433 --> 54:18.533 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
And construction is
expected to increase.

54:18.533 --> 54:23.233 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JEFF CORDELL: There's going to
be much more need for coastal
infrastructure and a lot

54:23.233 --> 54:28.233 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
more thinking about how we can
best create habitat for the
organisms that we're removing

54:28.700 --> 54:30.833 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
it from.

54:30.833 --> 54:34.000 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
KEN CHRISTENSEN: Once
the seawall is complete,
Cordell plans to begin
a decade-long monitoring

54:34.000 --> 54:37.000 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
project to figure out if it
does what it's supposed to.

54:37.000 --> 54:41.000 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JEFF CORDELL: Even that
brown stuff needs a good
amount of sunlight to grow.

54:41.000 --> 54:45.400 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
KEN CHRISTENSEN: If the
experiment succeeds,
the Seattle waterfront's
biggest change could

54:45.400 --> 54:49.433 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
be the change it inspires in
seawalls around the world.

